<segment id="1" parent="1001" relname="preparation">3. Methodology</segment>
<segment id="2" parent="1002" relname="preparation">Conventional</segment>
<segment id="3" parent="1002" relname="joint">DEA models can only consider output expansion or input contraction , but not both .</segment>
<segment id="4" parent="1004" relname="span">For the hotel industry , the output-oriented approach cannot distinguish between quasi-fixed inputs and variable inputs ,</segment>
<segment id="5" parent="4" relname="circumstance">while the input-oriented model ignores the existence of quasi-fixed inputs .</segment>
<segment id="6" parent="1006" relname="span">Moreover , the primary goal of tourist hotels is to expand outputs</segment>
<segment id="7" parent="6" relname="antithesis">rather than to contract inputs .</segment>
<segment id="8" parent="1008" relname="span">The directional distance function ,</segment>
<segment id="9" parent="1009" relname="span">capable of expanding outputs and contracting inputs simultaneously ,</segment>
<segment id="10" parent="9" relname="elaboration">can fulfill the requirements of this study .</segment>
<segment id="11" parent="1011" relname="span">In addition ,</segment>
<segment id="12" parent="1013" relname="span">because they may have different national cultures , operational philosophies , and managerial modes , different types of tourist hotels</segment>
<segment id="13" parent="12" relname="elaboration">( for instance , domestic hotels and international chain hotels )</segment>
<segment id="14" parent="1012" relname="same_unit">should thus own different efficiency frontiers .</segment>
<segment id="15" parent="1016" relname="span">A meta-frontier approach is able to measure efficiencies of decision making units</segment>
<segment id="16" parent="15" relname="elaboration">( DMUs )</segment>
<segment id="17" parent="1016" relname="elaboration">associated with distinctive technologies .</segment>
<segment id="18" parent="1007" relname="joint">3.1 .</segment>
